< review>
Stopped by because of all the positive reviews but my experience was the complete opposite.  I took my car in and decided to the get the top treatment ($25).  I highlighted some mud stains and bird poop on that car and I asked them to focus on cleaning those areas.  When the car came out of the "car wash" section - those areas had not been cleaned well and the stains were still visible.  I asked again for them to clean those areas and they said they would take care of it in the "drying" section.  I went other there and reminded them that those areas needed to be cleaned and the guy asked me to stand away from the car and wait for him to call me over.  When he told me the car was done - I again pointed out the stains and he told me that the mud and bird poop could not we washed off.  I gave him an incredulous look and he just said - they can't be cleaned, handed me my keys, called me annoying (in Spanish) to his co-worker, and told me to drive off.  A really bad experience and terrible job.  I will not be going back.< /review>

<gmapID>0x8085613c0b4ce09f:0x2d952abfb1bb89a3<//gmapID>< Text>
Wanted to find a place that hand washes, but didn't want to pay for a full detail. Found some good reviews and decided to come here. Guess they took an automated wash structure and turned it into a hand wash facility. It's a little hard to see from the street, but it's located on the grounds of the 76 gas station. One guy washes your car and the rest are ready to vacuum and dry off your car. Doesn't seem to be any posted prices, so that might be an issue, but ended up being $13 for a compact sedan. Definitely the best deal in the area.

Took my SUV there a week later and it was $15 for the same level of service. My only wish is that they would wipe down the seats too.</Text>

< Text>
My favorite local shop. Most of the staff has been there a while,  and they're always happy to help unlike some other shops in the area who try to pull off some Operator vibe all the time.

There's a small consignment selection of pistols and usually a good variety of long guns and shotguns.  I've seen everything from vintage .22s to  M14s in their used rifles.

There is also a huge selection of gear for the home gun smithing crowd, a good selection of knives and a wide variety of pepper spray for your non-lethal self defense.

One of the best things here- there's always a gung ho movie playing on the TV in the store.</Text>

The only thing you want to keep an eye on is, the prices are questionable. They are very expensive even considering the pandemic. If you are not in a hurry, I would suggest do some research and shop online, it's not that hard. And you can see glock, M9, mossberg available every week here and there. You can get info on Calguns, reddit and other places.

If you are really desperate and need a gun right now, well, this place gets the job done. But the price is like..they are not expecting you to come back and shop again.<//Text>

< review>
I bought a glock from this store based on the positive google reviews.  I was shown a gun with scuff marks on the slide serration.  I pointed it out and the guy behind the counter said he will get me another one.

He showed me another one which appeared not to have the scuff mark.  He took the gun behind the counter to fill out the paper work.  He then printed out the forms with the guns serial number and had me sign.  At that point, I simply checked the gun‚Äôs serial number and signed the forms.  First mistake on my end.

I come back after 10 days and it was a different guy behind the counter.  I gave the gun a cursory glance once more and signed the papers.  Second mistake on my end again.

I get home and start examining the gun and I see the same scuff mark on the same area of the first gun shown to me.  You can only see it at certain angles but it still there and it bothers me every time I see it.

Now, I decided not to pursue it figuring the store was unlikely to replace it anyway and decided to shoot the gun the next day.  That is on me since I did not want to wait to go to the store show them plus I was excited to shoot.  I blame myself for not checking the gun one last
time before taking possession.

I probably won‚Äôt buy my guns from here in the future because I believe I was sold the first gun shown to me with the scuff marks.  Was it intentionally swapped or accidental?  I honestly don‚Äôt know.

Now I know in a year or two, the slide will probably show some scuffing/scratches due to wear.  However it‚Äôs like buying a new car, you want it blemish free when you buy it new and you accept it if you put the dings or scratches there yourself.

Bottom line, if you decide to go to this store, make sure to inspect your gun thoroughly again before you sign the paper work when you verify the serial number when you buy it and before you pick it up.</review>

<date>1339188142927<//date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
I purchased a rifle from Bay Area Gun Vault yesterday June 7th, 2012.

This is my first go at an AR and the man who i believe to be either the owner or manager of the store whose name is Gary was the most patient and helpful person I could have had the pleasure to deal with. He explained in great detail the differences between the rifles he had and was very willing to go more in depth if I had a question or didn't fully understand.
Going beyond showing me the weapons and telling me the price and taking time to make sure i was well educated is what gives them an excellent rating in my book.

I could have got a cheaper price online but i'm happy to support local business for the hundred or so bucks they will make.

I'd also like to add that people who complain about the attitude or attentions of the people in the Gun Vault probably went in with a bad attitude to begin with or were walking around with their head down like they didn't want to be talk to. Just like anything else in life be good to the people you're interacting with and they will be good to you.< /Review>

I told gary about all of this and he agreed to give me time to figure out what this was about. I refiled my dros and this time, it came back as "undetermined". I have no felonies, I've never been institutionalized, there was no actual reason for the undetermined. Gary refused to release to me, claiming he felt I would be a liability. <pictures>None</pictures><rate>5</rate>< Text>
I am amazed at the complaints in some of these reviews. I have been to this shop regularly for a couple of years now and have had nothing but excellent service and pricing.
The incident that won them my business was a couple years ago in the middle of the ammo drought I was looking for .22. I found a couple of boxes of CCI at another shop that was charging 19.95 per 100 rnd box. Needing more I found Bay Area Gun Vault online and stopped by, they had the same ammo for 9.99. This was the only shop I found that was not gouging for ammo. From then on they have had the majority of my business.
The sales people listen to me and then present what I would be interested in (they are almost too good at this). One of the things I hated at other shops is the constant pushing of AR style weapons. I am not interested in ARs and as such have met with rudeness at other shops. Not the case here, they realize that the way to sell a weapon is to present something the customer would be interested in.
Four starts for BAGV< /Text>

< text>
Did my first ever FFL transfer.  I went in to talk to them on recommendation from a friend prior to finalizing my out of state purchase.  They let me know the process as far as what to do and expect.  Once I received notification that my purchase was delivered, I went in to do the transfer.  At the same time, I needed to get my FSC(thanks California) which we squared away first.  The process was simple, the young man who helped me was informative and friendly, and I had my DROS in under an hour, FSC and all.  Clean store, lots of goodies and accessories to choose from, definitely a place where I will purchase from in the future.</text>

Instead of greeting or anything like that, his very first question is "Are you a US Citizen". I say yes.
There is a decent selection of firearms but the layout feels a little cramped. Also don't know why the staff has handguns on their holsters. Just for impressing clientele? (Although this is not unique to this particluar shop). Further staff does not acknowledge their lack of knowledge on a certain firearm but tries to bluster through. On a specific handgun they quoted some 4 months of waiting time, while its available almost immediately online.
Sticker prices for a standard m1a walnut stock are 1695, which amounts to about 1830 when including ffl and dros. you can get that for 1375 online, which amounts to about 1475 including ffl/dros/shipping.
Since the cost/service isn't outstanding, i can't recommend this shop. You can drop by to browse through the collection, but i can't recommend buying anything.

<Date>1348490354496<//Date>< Text>
Went to look around. After being ignored for a while, longer than it should have been as the staff was in a heated discussion among themselves about the merits of two black rifle brands, a short stocky guy attempted to help me. Great, finally, there was fairly poor attitiude all the way around but these guys were not on par with the jerks at Tabors up the road in San Bruno.

To gauge honesty I did not let on my 35 yrs overall arms experience that included 20 yrs mil/LEO, 10 years professional gunsmithing, and 20 years competitive shooting.

As a point of reference I showed interest in a M4. They tried to up sell me like crazy. The retail prices were competitive but by no means the best that could be found. Since I buy wholesale I was really just looking around for fun but wanted to see what kind of place this is.

I asked a couple of questions of which I knew the answers to and realized they did not have a good handle on the topic.

On the way out (I was not buying on this trip), I was directed to look at their "vintage" guns as a last chance to well me something. "We got a good selection of WW2 guns" he said. Yeah, now we are talking. I have an extensive collection of standard issue, M1C, and M1D Garands (equivalant CMP Rack to Collector grades) and have rebuilt maybe 25 of them for clients. I know Garands,

The junk they tried to palm off was clearly rack grade (no I did not gauge them) but the pitting and wear marks told the tale - BUTwith GREAT stories attached. How he knew this particular weapon was used in the WW2 PTO is still a mystery - I should have asked.

Conclusion - good parking, fair to just about retail pricing, inexperienced help.

If you are a newbie and want to bust your gun cherry - you will likely be wowed, if you know much you will not be overlly impressed.

Maybe I should have bought that Garand that went ashore at Iwo Jima . . . it was only marked up 300% above it's actual value BUT it had a great story, what a steal!</Text>

< text>
Very poor customer service.  If a crowd is getting a little too rowdy, they should talk to a responsible/sober one in the group about it so we can get the rest of our group in line.  What happened instead was the VERY rude gal just cleared our table, taking our wine glasses and all, even before we had finished all the tastings we already paid for.  We were stunned and didn't know what was happening or why she was being so rude.  She never actually told us to leave or that we were being kicked out.  She just took everything away and left us wondering WTH.  It wasn't until I went to her that she told me that part of our group was being rowdy in another part of the building.  I was very surprised that she didn't bother to communicate with us about it before or after.  For a business whose success is based on CUSTOMERS, it was amazing how POORLY these customers were treated.  I know none of us will be back to Municipal Winemakers.  Too many other great places nearby for us to put up with this one.  Hopefully they will learn to treat their customers better.<//text>

After looking on yelp she found SweetHoney Dessert. It's located in a small plaza with plenty of parking. Anyway walking in...the interior is super clean and modern. This place is a Hong Kong style dessert place with different types of Hong Kong desserts like sago and sticky rice.

I wasn't super particularly hungry but I found the coconut milk sago with palm something and ordered that. My sister then went to order the mango smoothie, coconut sago with a side of fresh cubed mango, and then some fried calamari rings.

The service was great and the server was super helpful with all our questions regarding the assortment of desserts. Also, if you check in on yelp you can get a discount off your entire order.

Side note my sister loved it so much she went back a couple days later with some other friends. I will probably go back if I'm in the area.< /text>< Rating>

< review>
I was totally disappointed after being amped up about trying this place out the whole day. The place is very nicely decorated with a modern touch. It is very clean and modern looking.  You can put your name on an iPad to be waitlisted. We ordered a mango pancake, it was the most disgusting thing I‚Äôve eaten, you get a sliver of sweetened mango, stuff in this thin doughy skin, filled with a bunch of whipped cream. How is that even considered pancake is beyond me. Took a bite and pretty much tasted whipped cream, what a waste of my calorie consumption for the day. Then we had the mango pomelo sago with black jello, this was a little below average with nothing spectacular and the taste is borderline bland. The pomelo made this dessert a little bitter. The calamari ring was decent, but too oily. The best dessert for me was their red bean sesame dessert with three rice balls. I had the least hope for this order, but it was the best. Overall, I would NOT recommend this place, the portion is small, the price is high, and the taste was below average.< /review>

Great bikes, friendly staff, and great deals, how can it get any better! Decided to rent bikes for the day to bike across the Golden Gate Bridge, and stumbled upon this place, which is located not far from free all day parking. They had a great deal on all day bike rentals, for both single and tandem bikes. I'm usually very picky about bikes, but the bikes here met all of my standards. The rental process was quick and simple, and the employees, especially Barry, were helpful in recommending route options.   If you are looking to rent bikes in San Francisco, there is no doubt Bike & View will be your one stop shop for all your bike rental needs. Give them a visit!</Review>

<username>Ahmad Amine< /username><pictures>None<//pictures>< Gmap_id>
0x808580db93060895:0xea1db35ac439bf28<//Gmap_id>
<Date>1531086356709</Date><user>117226940050391599822</user>< review>
My worst experience so far in San Francisco. No wonder the bikes are 30% off if you book online: their quality sucks.
To start it off, the bike was noisy from the very beginning as it creaked frequently, especially when changing gears.
Later on in my ride around the coast, the chain slid off the gears when i put the bike in first gear. I was shook and scared but luckily it sorted itself out when i moved it a little.
The gear changes were oh so terrible. Every time i changed gears the transition is sudden that it could take someone less experienced off balance.
The worst part is when i was going up to legion's honor (anyone who has been there knows that its very steep) and logically i had to put the bike in the lowest gear possible. And just so I did. And just so did the chain slip again, this time for good. I had to hike the whole climb up to legion of honor then walk the bike down all the way to get myself a bus back to the trans-bay terminal to return to Berkeley.
I had to haul the broken bike with me between buses till i was back home because the shop closes at 7 and i was way out by 6:30 when this happened.
Luckily i had paid a 4$ insurance that covered the broken parts of the repairs (didn't cover the price of the buses i had to take and the struggle of hauling the bike around).
I did lose the helmet in all the confusion however. THIS was my fault and i expected to pay for it 10-20$.
This brings us to the worst part of the whole experience: the customer service. When i delivered the bike i complained to the lady there that the experience was bad because the chain slipped and i had to carry it around. The lady simply didn't care. All she cared for was the missing helmet to which she charged me 25$. She even had the audacity to tell me that they usually cost them 45$ as if trying to make me feel bad for paying 25$! It's also weird that some people compliment the service. For me, the service was very bland and I didn't receive a map of the area like some people said they got or like most other bike rentals.
The place closes at 7 and you need to get the bike before 6:45 so expect to keep the bike if you wish to explore enough of the bay (i was still exploring fort point by 5 when i took the bike at 2).
TL:DR: Unacceptable bike quality and bad customer service. Don't be lured by the 30% off discount, it's there for a reason. Pay a few bucks extra and rent from more reliable bike rentals.<//review>

<rating>5< /rating>< review>
This place was literally 10 mins walk from our hotel. Renting was pretty easy - we booked online and then showed up next morning around 10am. They made us sign some waivers - gave us the maps of suggested places to stop at on our way to Sausalito and off we went ! It was mostly downhill or flat from the shop and we stopped at almost all the points on the map (Wave Organ being my personal favorite!). Getting on to the bridge is the only steep uphill and the bikes were actually able to gear-shift through the ride, powered by my burning knees ofcourse. Downhill to Sausalito past  Golden Gate Vista point was the most fun and highly recommended. Once in Sausalito, we parked our bikes at the ferry terminal, purchased our return tickets, grabbed food and beer at Joinery and then hopped back on the ferry to SF. All in all an amazing experience to bike the bridge - highly recommended!<//review>

second, that the tour ends at the port of Sausalito.

This means you have to drive back across the bridge alone or take the ferry for about $ 25 (2 people).

supplemented or more clearly expressed.
Otherwise, a highlight that was missing on any sightseeing from San Francisco.

Especially positive, we noticed the tour guide,
who cared very carefully our group with about 20 people,
Therefore an honest and 100% recommendation from us.

< Text>
Daniel is a great person of contact, we moved from out of state and he was able to handle everything remotely without an issue. The complex is beautiful and is very pet friendly with a little fenced in area for dogs to run freely right on the side of the property. There is security patrolling the area, but I am concerned with the ease of non residents being able to access the facilities. There is a gate at the front of the complex but it remains open long enough for cars to tag along behind you. The pool and workout areas are accessed with a keyfob but I've seen other residents open the gate/doors for strangers who ask to get in. We've been here for about three weeks and I've seen the security guard several times throughout the day, which puts me at ease. It still makes me uneasy about these people potentially breaking into my mailbox, I wish those were more secure or had obvious security cameras.

But the complex is gorgeous and modern with nice utilities and a friendly staff.<//Text>

<rating>5<//rating>< Text>
I lost my personal insurance blue shield plan when Obamacare came in to play.
Since then, I have had to have medi-cal.
On 6/12 a family member called her dental office‚Äã on my behalf (I couldn't speak I was in that much pain.)  I had a very infected molar & was in a LOT of pain. I couldn't believe it when they said to come in right away even with medi-cal! That's a dentist that cares!  Since having medi-cal for myself and young twins, I have never gotten such a rapid response for Doctors. I was literally immediately taken back once I arrived and very promptly taken care of.  I am still recovering from going in a couple days ago, my tooth indeed was very bad. Also, Dr. Taitz gave me antibiotics but also knew that I'd need a stronger pain reliever and prescribed a few days worth of norco as well. I don't like to take medicine unless I really need it....but boy I sure needed it.
My point is, she was courteous (her and the very sweet lady that works with her) completely shocked me by taking me right then and with medi-cal; and writing prescriptions she knew I would need when I went home to heal.
I will return to her and refer her simply because of what she did for me. She didn't know me from Adam. She went above and beyond and located right down the street from my home.  In & out fast. I'm hoping my mouth finishes its' healing this weekend.
**Very grateful and thankful to this office**</Text>

< review>
I would not recommend this place.  All is good until it‚Äôs time to renew your lease.  That‚Äôs when they get you.  They don‚Äôt let you renew at the Market rate of the apartment.  For example if the market rate right now for your specific apartment unit is $2000, i.e that‚Äôs what a new person coming in will pay.  That‚Äôs the quote the new person will get.  However the current resident, will pay around $2200 to renew the lease for that same apartment unit (they charge you an approx 10% premium above the market rate to renew each year).  I found this very unfair, and when I asked them about it, they said, well you will have to pay that much in moving costs if you go somewhere else, so you might as well stay here.  Such a ridiculous answer by the manager Jennifer!  Other apartment complexes do not do this.</review>

< review>
You will pay full price for cleaning, paint, and carpet cleaning regardless of what your pre-move out inspection tells you. Even if the cleaning log says they only wiped down the appliances and small marks on the wall (normal wear and tear per the pre-move out inspector).
Cleaning $118
Paint $26
Carpet $125

If you are looking at apartment 8028 be prepared to be threatened by your new lovely downstairs neighbors who also threatened the police one day and I saw him get thrown to the ground and restrained (that was the day I stopped thinking his threats and his wife's yelling were empty).

Goodluck. Another piece of advice, don't live on the second floor no matter how small your dog is (my dog weighs < 30lbs but my neighbors were constantly banging on the ceiling when him or I walked around and we go to bed at 9:30pm, not later).<//review>

< Review>
A step above most small mall theaters! Of course the theaters are smaller; seating maybe only around 50 - 100 people BUT they didnt scrimp on screen size,sound quality,or amenities! Most of the theaters have big comfy power reclining seats! The lack of actual people manning the box office (because of kiosks) and at the concession stand (because of the size of the theater) does make it feel a little deserted BUT at the same time, when you're  sitting in the theater,it feels like your at friends home theater so it's kind of comfortable. Very small theaters here.  The theater spaces "inside-a-shopping-mall" was never originally designed to accommodate big theaters, but they managed to squeeze some entertainment venues in here to help meet the demand. <Text>Nothing to complain about this place, really. It has everything you might want if you want to watch a chill movie:

1.) Parking spots (PLENTY)
2.) Reclining seats
3.) Small theater (If you don't appreciate huge crowds)
4.) Self serve kiosks.
5.) Lots of dining places outside the theater.

They don't have IMAX or Dolby though, but that's why it's beside AMC 16. I still think this is the go to place for movies not IMAX or Dolby worthy.</Text></record>

< review>
There are 3 AMCs in downtown Burbank; this is the smallest. It's situated on the top floor of the Media Center mall itself and tends to have both mainstream and some art house movies. The theatres are smaller than the AMC 16 in the next block south, but comfortable, and there are often smaller  crowds for otherwise hard to see movies.
It's a good little theatre. You can use the mall parking, which is always available, but more so after hours, when only the theatre is open.<//review>

< Text>
The totally remodeled the theater.  Every seats are now electric recliner.  The screen are also bigger and nicer.  It gives you a very intimate feeling especially the smaller room.  The staffs here are friendly and helpful for the most part.

The concession stand could use a little cleaning up throughout the day.  Every-time we have been here, it‚Äôs usually a mess.  The trash is always full for some reason.

Since they redid the theater.  You can reserve and choose your seats.  I don‚Äôt have to rush to the theater.  I buy my ticket online and skip the whole line.  Speaking of the box office.  There are 3 new big touch screen self service kiosks with 1 customers service station/box office.

Parking is located in the mall on the 4th floor of the parking structure.  We never have any issue with finding parking.  I much preferred going here than the older AMC 16 down the street with the rundown seats, horrible parking, and long concessions line.<//Text>

I was very surprised at the quality of this little theater. We were in theater 8. Despite being small, it was very high quality. My two complaints would be rows one and two are too close to actually take the movie in. Second, the right speaker was feet away from the wall and cast a decent sized shadow on the screen. Seats recline almost completely, so this could also work for someone looking to take a nap.< /Text>

< user_name>
J Servin< /user_name>
<time>1452135411783< /time><rate>3</rate>< text>
Tiny theater nestled inside the Burbank mall. It's not busy due to the AMC 16 that's walking distance away but, it's also not updated or any cheaper considering.

They're usually playing some of current movies, as well as some more obscure cinema. It's a place you'd go if you're trying to watch a movie nearing the end of its run or, maybe a movie you're trying to bring younger children to.

The seating is pretty limited and, the seats themselves don't rock, recline, or do much in the way of comfort.

The snack bar is also dated. No where near the choices the larger nearby theater has.

All in all its... Okay.</text>
